'''Phil Tippett''' is a movie director and an award-winning [[Wikipedia:Visual effects|visual effects]] supervisor and producer, who specializes in creature design and character animation. Although uncredited, Tippett portrayed the character of [[Myo]] in [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']].<ref name="Cinefantastique">Mandell, Paul. 1978. "Rick Baker, Doug Beswick, Laine Liska&mdash;2nd Unit Makeup Cantina." [[Wikipedia:Cinefantastique|''Cinefantastique'']] Double Issue Vol6No4/Vol7No1: p66–71.</ref>

==Biography==
[[File:PhilTippettTauntaun-TESB40.png|thumb|left|250px|Phil Tippett with a tauntaun model]]
In 1978, Phil Tippett headed the [[Industrial Light & Magic]] (ILM) animation department with [[Jon Berg]] for [[Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|''Star Wars'': Episode V ''The Empire Strikes Back'']]. Tippett used [[Wikipedia:Stop motion|stop motion]] to animate [[All Terrain Armored Transport (Galactic Civil War)|Imperial walkers]] and the [[tauntaun]]. By 1983, Tippett led the famed [[Lucasfilm]] creature shop for [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Return of the Jedi'']], for which he was awarded an Oscar in 1984.

In [[2006]], Tippett wrote the afterword for the ''[[Sculpting a Galaxy: Inside the Star Wars Model Shop]]'' reference book.

Tippett worked on the [[Karthon Chop Fields]] in the [[The Mandalorian Season Two|second season]] of the series ''[[Star Wars: The Mandalorian]]'', and also helped design the ruins of [[Mandalore]] in [[The Mandalorian Season Three|third season]].<ref name="Phil Tippett Mandalore">{{OfficialYouTube|channel=@yahooentertainment|name=Yahoo Entertainment|video=rLI9eib0PRM|text=Jon Favreau and Dave Filoni talk 'Mandalorian' Season 3, tease new Baby Yoda reveals|archivedate=20230315174522}}</ref>

